<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 94 / Gangs move into bootleg beer business: Protection rackets
put pressure on pub landlords to allow illegal sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Criminal gangs that run pub protection rackets are reported to be muscling
in on Britain's booming business in cross-Channel bootlegging by
intimidating inner-city pub landlords.
Bootleggers have told some Sunderland and Newcastle licensees to co-operate
in making it easier to distribute illegally imported beer, according to Mr
Frank Nicholson, managing director of Vaux, the Sunderland-based brewer and
pub owner.
The government has refused to cut import duties on alcoholic drinks and
tobacco to make imports from France less lucrative. And it has played down
reports that organised crime has infiltrated beer bootlegging, although it
recognises the problem exists with tobacco imports.
However, Mr Nicholson says, there is clear evidence that some bootlegging is
being organised by the criminals who run pub protection rackets.
'I am alarmed because it is a new element to an old vice, and the avenues to
do it are very easy to exploit. It is a neat extension of their business,'
he said.
Bootleggers have 'suggested' actions to some Vaux licensees. The most
popular include: selling smuggled beer in their bars; turning a blind eye to
it being sold in their car parks; and opening their pubs later than usual to
ensure more people are at home when the bootleggers take a sales trip around
the neighbourhood.
'I have seen myself bootleggers selling beer from a van outside one of our
Sunderland pubs,' said Mr Nicholson. 'The pub car park is a good meeting
point.'
Protection racketeers often threaten landlords with violence or damage to
their property, although Mr Nicholson said he was not yet aware of any
bootleg-related violence.
Typical consequences of failure to comply with protection rackets are damage
to property and starting fights in bars.
Rumours of intimidation by bootleggers began to circulate in the trade
earlier this year, but Mr Nicholson is the first brewer to go on the record
about the problems his landlords face.
A London brewer told Mr Nicholson of a similar experience in Croydon, south
London, when they met at the Brewers and Licensed Retailers Association
earlier this week.
Mr Nicholson, who said the problem was confined to tough, inner-city
neighbourhoods, has also had direct reports of intimidation in Manchester.
'Organised gangs and intimidation are an inevitable part of bootlegging,'
the association said.
The brewing industry estimates that some 3.5 per cent to 4 per cent of beer
sold in Britain - or some 15 per cent of beer consumed at home - is imported
from France.
Vaux encourages its landlords to tell it about cases of intimidation,
bootlegging and protection rackets so it can work with the police to stamp
them out. But Mr Nicholson said he was sympathetic to those who did not want
to talk to the brewery because of the dangers. He says the solution is
two-fold: the government must reduce the financial attractions of
bootlegging, while brewers and publicans must work with the police to combat
crime.
</TEXT>
