<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 94 / Letters to the Editor: Favourable tax regime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr TORLACH DENIHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your article, 'Boost for Dublin's tax haven' (December 8), reporting
the decision of the European Commission to extend the marketing deadline for
Dublin's International Financial Services Centre, refers to the centre as a
'tax haven'.
Such pejorative language is totally inappropriate. The rate of corporation
tax on the profits of companies in the International Financial Services
Centre is 10 per cent exactly, the same rate applicable to the profits of
manufacturing companies in Ireland.
Some 220,000 people are employed in manufacturing industry in Ireland, of
whom some 90,000 are employees of foreign-owned industrial enterprises.
These companies are attracted by a favourable corporation tax regime and the
European Union's youngest and best educated workforce. The same features
attract companies to the centre.
Your correspondent should be aware that the European Commission is not in
the business of approving tax havens and that its decision vindicates how
the centre has evolved over the past seven years.
Torlach Denihan,
director,
Financial Services Industry Association,
84-86 Lower Baggot Street,
Dublin 2, Ireland
</TEXT>
