<DOCNO>FT944-1721</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-ELSDLACGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941219
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Like many winning formulas, Picture This (10pm BBC2) is so simple you wonder
why nobody thought of it before. Prompted by a miner's disdainful remark
(nemesis later strikes) about lavatory-cleaning, the programme constructs a
chain (no pun intended) of apparently undesirable jobs, throwing up much
professional pride and personal integrity. The toilet cleaner in turn would
never stoop to prostitution - cue a prostitute (Central Casting stuff, this:
a dominatrix with all the gear) who whips her punters but hates cruelty to
animals: cue a sympathetic abattoir-worker, and so on. The absence of
television critics from this display of fragile dignity makes a curious
omission.
The stale flavour of cliche permeates Milner (9.30 BBC1): the seedy
investigative lawyer with marriage problems, snooty colleagues, seeming
inadequacy - the formulaic anti-hero, in fact. Mel Smith tries to make it as
a straight actor, amiable but not really convincing, supported by an
unexciting cast of decent second-raters.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4832 Radio Broadcasting Stations.
    P4833 Television Broadcasting Stations.
    P4841 Cable and Other Pay Television Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
