<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 94 / Business Travel: US air safety
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Air travel in the US over Christmas could be severely disrupted following
the grounding of dozens of commerical flights because of a crackdown on
commuter airline safety standards. At the weekend American Eagle suspended
all commuter operations to mid-west cities for the second time in less than
a week, and Kiwi International Airlines suspended all services.
Crashes have given US aviation its worst safety record in six years, with
the pall over the commuter airline industry deepened by two American Eagle
crashes in five weeks that killed 83 people. The result is that some
travellers have been scrambling for rental cars rather than short-hop
flights.
Prompted by last week's crash of an American Eagle UK-built Jetstream Super
31 (a two-engined turbo-prop), US transportation secretary Federico Pena
said that commuter airlines in the US faced more safety inspections and
their crews would get more rest under new safety rules.
He said American Eagle has been observing the safety standards required for
larger aircraft, but that the authorities would start an immediate safety
audit of every US carrier, large or small. In addition, commuter airline
safety standards would be elevated to match those of regular airlines.
Pena set a 100-day deadline for this to be achieved. 'We are very troubled
by the number of accidents we've had this year,' he said.
An American Eagle spokesman said the company had complete confidence in the
type of aircraft it uses.
</TEXT>
<XX>
