FT  19 DEC 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI, TV editor of Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Channel Four's business series High Interest has been given a new title and
a later slot (Tuesday, December 20, 9.00-9.45pm) for its programme on Anne
Summers. The sex shop company only agreed to participate in the programme
because of the business angle. It presents a fascinating look at the
company's marketing success.
Body fluids will be spilled in Rumble In The Jungle (Friday, Dec 23,
9.00-9.45pm, BBC2), which looks at the bloody, sweaty world heavyweight
boxing match between George Foreman and an out-of-condition Muhammad Ali.
Two decades on, this documentary assesses how extraordinary a feat it was.
An equally weighty Victoria Wood does a sketch about a fat aerobics
instructor in her Christmas Special (Sunday, Dec 25, 9.40-10.30pm, BBC1),
although nowadays she needs padding to play the part.
On the other side, real fat ladies will be singing in Elijah Moshinsky's
production of Aida (Dec 25, 7.00-9.35pm, BBC2). It features Cheryl Studer
and Dennis O'Neill. Channel Four's operatic offering is Turandot (Dec 25,
3.15-5.20pm) with sets and costumes by David Hockney. Tune in for the last
act if you only want to listen to Nessun Dorma. There is more opera the
following day with a two-part profile of Verdi (Tuesday, Dec 27,
5.00-6.00pm, BBC2).
Singers of a different strain take over with Flanders and Swann (Tuesday,
Dec 27, 6.50-7.30pm, BBC2) - a tribute to mark the death of Donald Swann
this year. A new generation will learn the joys of being a gnu.
An Equinox Special (Wednesday, Dec 28, 8.30-10.00pm, C4) takes a magnifying
glass to forensic science. DNA profiling and finger-printing were thought to
be unassailable methods of identification, but a growing number of experts
are wondering if these aids to crime detection are quite as infallible as
they initially seemed to be.
