<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 94 / Conservative Party Funding: Flow of funds slowed as hard
times hit - How the Conservative party raises money from industry has long
been one of the great puzzles of UK political life. In a special report,
Peter Marsh, with William Lewis, Jimmy Burns, Roland Adburgham and Robert
Peston, unravels some aspects of the mystery / Business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, WILLIAM LEWIS, JIMMY BURNS, ROLAND ADBURGHAM and ROBERT
PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The problems faced by East Midlands Industrial Council in recent years are
typical of those which have affected the other nine industrial councils of
England and Wales.
Several council members, who were involved in raising funds for the
Conservative party and attended regular meetings with government ministers,
have been forced by the region's economic downturn to scale back their
involvement and concentrate on their businesses.
Mr Tony Budge, who resigned his chairmanship of the council at the end of
1992 when the family company AF Budge collapsed, said the council reached
its peak in the late-1980s boom years. He said: 'Industrial councils have
suffered in line with disenchantment with politics and the Conservative
party in recent years.' Mr Budge chaired the council from 1987 and is still
a member of the party.
'The council's success was a product of the Thatcher era, when there was a
government which was asking business what it should be looking at,' he said.
Members of the council, which was at its most influential in the late 1980s,
would take two or three personal business contacts to occasional meetings
with ministers in the House of Commons. Mr Budge said: 'It was not harmful
for our own business to take our suppliers and other people with whom we
worked, and give them an opportunity to get involved.'
A small office in Grantham, Baroness Thatcher's birthplace, acts as the
headquarters of the East Midlands council, while meetings are usually held
in Newark. The council's fundraising target for this year is believed to
have been about Pounds 400,000 but members believe that no more than Pounds
120,000 has been raised.
Council chairman Mr Colin MacLeod, chairman and owner of Newark-based
Caledonian Mining, said: 'I have been on the council about seven years and
this year is the worst (for fundraising). I have never seen anything like
this.'
As well as difficulties in raising money, some members of the council are
scaling down their involvement. Mr Budge - having recently bought several AF
Budge subsidiaries from the receiver - has no intention of becoming actively
involved again, although he is still a member. Several other members
describe their membership as 'in name only'. At least one, Mr David
McErlain, former chairman of Anglo United, plans to resign.
Mr McErlain, who has raised Pounds 100,000 for the party in the past five
years, said that the role of the industrial councils was clear: 'They are a
straight money-raising unit of the party. It is a joke to say that they have
anything to do with the relationship between the government and industry.'
He said being a member of a council 'is like being a member of the party
without having a ticket'.
Sir Michael Bishop, chairman of British Midland, the airline, said he was a
member of the council 'in a personal capacity, not in a corporate sense'.
Sir Peter Mansfield, professor of physics at Nottingham University, said he
was invited on to the council by Mr Budge. He was picked as an academic to
broaden the council's membership beyond business executives. He said the
council had 'little contact' with the local Conservative party association
and had been 'fairly inactive for about six months', while a new secretary,
Maj Michael Hankinson, was appointed.
Ms Jean Parker, director of Grantham-based Vacu-Lug Traction Tyres, is the
only female member of the council and one of only a very small number of
women members in England and Wales.
She said: 'It was not a condition of my appointment that I go out and raise
money. At dinners there is generally some kind of appeal for funds but most
of us industrialists have got thick skins and do not feel obliged to
respond.' She regards herself as a 'fringe member' of the council.
Mr Reg Brealey, chairman of Indian jute company Titaghur and of Sheffield
United Football Club, is also a member but has not played an active role for
a number of years.
</TEXT>
<XX>
