<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 94 / Insurance policy fraud 'cut by 25%'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, Insurance Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Insurance companies have succeeded in cutting fraudulent claims by about 25
per cent in the past two years, says an Association of British Insurers
survey released yesterday.
The association calculates, however, that fraudulent claims, estimated at
Pounds 600m this year, still add about 4 per cent to the cost of insurance.
Mr Mark Boleat, director-general, said efforts at preventing fraud were 'now
beginning to pay off, with signs of a fall in the number and cost of
fraudulent claims. There is still some way to go and that is why further
anti-fraud initiatives can be expected from the insurance companies'.
Creditor insurance policies, which provide protection against unemployment
when goods are bought on credit, are most prone to fraud. For such policies
the cost of fraud is worth about 6 per cent of premiums. Household policies
are also vulnerable.
</TEXT>
