<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 94 / High Court to rule on BCCI payout plan today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The painstaking progress towards a settlement for the creditors' of the
failed Bank of Credit and Commerce International moves forward today at the
High Court in London.
The latest plan put forward by the UK-based liquidators, accountants Touche
Ross, must be cleared by the court before arrangements can be made for the
payment of an interim dividend to the creditors.
But success today will not remove all the obstacles facing the creditors.
The agreement has to be cleared by courts in three jurisdictions - the UK,
Luxembourg and the Cayman Islands. Any court decision may be subject to an
appeal.
So far the case has been heard in Luxembourg but a judgment is not expected
until January 12. The case comes before the courts in the Cayman Islands on
January 12 as well. Today's hearing in London is expected to last a day.
While appeals lodged in the UK courts or the Cayman Islands can be dealt
with relatively swiftly, an unsuccessful appeal in the Luxembourg court
could delay a payment to creditors by up to a year. A successful one would
derail the agreement.
An earlier creditors' plan had to be abandoned after a successful appeal was
granted by the Luxembourg court in October last year. The current plan, the
second offered to creditors, was designed to meet objections raised during
that appeal.
BCCI was shut down in 1991 with liabilities of up to Dollars 10bn following
the discovery of the world's biggest banking fraud. The bank's assets may
total up to Dollars 4bn. Estimates of the number of creditors worldwide
range up to 150,000.
Under the new agreement the Abu Dhabi government, the principal shareholder
of BCCI, will pay Dollars 1.55bn after the successful completion of the
court hearings, Dollars 150m 24 months later and Dollars 100m 36 months
after completion.
The eventual dividend to creditors was estimated shortly after the collapse
of the bank at between 30 per cent to 40 per cent and throughout the lengthy
process of finding an acceptable agreement most forecasts have kept within
that band.
However, the final offer could well be outside this range because of
unresolved legal actions linked to the bank's collapse and uncertainty over
the final level of claims by creditors - particularly those outside the UK
and Luxembourg.
Estimates of an interim dividend have been put at about 20 per cent. This is
based on creditors' claims of about Dollars 10bn and funds available to the
liquidators from the Abu Dhabi settlement and other sources.
The current plan received a boost when it was welcomed by the BCCI
Depositors Protection Association.
The association had been responsible for helping to block the original
offer. It said it wished to end the delays caused by appeals.
It also pointed out that the new agreement, unlike the original, allowed
creditors to pursue claims against the government of Abu Dhabi.
An appeal against the agreement is possible from a range of interested
parties. These include regulators, directors of the failed bank and former
employees, as well as individual creditors.
</TEXT>
