FT  19 DEC 94 / Middle-class crisis identified
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Government mistakes and the 'feel-flat recovery' are breeding a dangerous
cynicism among the middle-classes, says a paper by the Social Market
Foundation.
The paper by Mr Matthew Symonds, a former Independent journalist, says that
the government's unpopularity can be traced to a growing 'culture of
anxiety' among middle-income voters. This, he argues, explains the lack of a
'feelgood' factor in the recovery to date. 'For 'feelgood', read 'feel
flat',' he says.
Mr Symonds adds: 'The middle classes feel a powerful sense of betrayal. They
feel that they have done all of the things they were asked to, and given
dutiful support to the orthodoxies of the 1980s and yet things have not
turned out well.'
The Middle Class Crisis, Social Market Foundation, 20 Queen Anne's Gate,
London SW1H 9AA.
