<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 94 / Service provides pension updates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Company finance directors are being offered a service which provides
immediate information on the assets and liabilities of their company pension
schemes.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy firm which has developed the service,
says much of the information on the state of a company's pension scheme is
out-of-date, sometimes by as much as three years, because it is based on the
triennial valuations of the fund's consulting actuary.
As a result a company may not be aware of looming deficiencies in its
pension fund which will eventually have an impact on the company's profit
and loss account.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand has developed a system which will give information on
pension funds on a monthly basis - or within hours if necessary - and
provide projections of its future performance.
It can also give up-to-date information on each employee's accrued pension
and its transfer value.
The accountancy firm's service is partly a response to the recent tightening
of pension regulations in the wake of the Robert Maxwell scandal, in which
Pounds 440m worth of pensioners' funds disappeared, and to new regulations
in the government's pension bill, published last week.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand said surpluses on many pension funds were being eroded
because of the lack of dividend growth on investments in the recession.
Mr Ralph Brereton, an actuary and pensions partner with Coopers &amp; Lybrand in
Edinburgh who devised the system, said: 'Companies should treat their
corporate pension funds with the same attention as they would give to a
major subsidiary. Yet often they haven't a clue because their most recent
information is the triennial report of the consulting actuary.'
Mr Brereton said a number of companies recently discovered that their
pension funds were heading towards deficiency because they had continued a
holiday from contributing to the fund when this was no longer justified.
He said: 'Their forward cash planning for the rest of their business has
been screwed up because they are having to resume making contributions.'
Companies have to record pension contributions in their profit and loss
account, but these are based on the most recent actuarial valuation.
A statutory instrument in 1992 required companies to treat a deficit on
their pension fund as a debt to the employer. This followed the pension
scandal which broke after Robert Maxwell's death in 1991.
The pensions bill contains provisions requiring companies to spread their
pension costs over the working life of an employee, and to check annually
that the scheme would be solvent if it had to be wound up. It will forbid
them to overfund their schemes.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand pioneered its system, which it says is the only one of its
kind, in 1992, and started marketing it widely this autumn. It is studying
ways of providing the software to companies which manage their own schemes.
Editorial Comment, Page 17
</TEXT>
