<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 94 / Carter starts peace mission
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Former US president Jimmy Carter yesterday began his peace mission to Bosnia
to try to break the diplomatic deadlock among the warring parties. As his
visit got under way, defeated Bosnian-government troops were withdrawing
from Velika Kladusa, a strategic town in the north-western Bihac pocket
which fell to Serb and renegade Moslem forces.
After meeting President Franjo Tudjman of Croatia, Mr Haris Silajdzic, the
Bosnian prime minister, and UN officials, in the Croatian capital Zagreb, Mr
Carter left for Sarajevo amid tight security. Earlier yesterday four
rocket-propelled grenades exploded near a UN anti-sniping team in the city
centre, slightly wounding a peacekeeper and a civilian. Today Mr Carter is
to meet Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, in Pale, the Serb
mountain stronghold above Sarajevo.
