<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 94 / Italian coalition totters as Bossi pulls out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The government of Mr Silvio Berlusconi, the Italian prime minister, looks
almost certain to be brought down in a no confidence vote on Wednesday after
the weekend defection of Mr Umberto Bossi, leader of the populist Northern
League.
The fall of the eight-month-old right-wing coalition would initiate a highly
unstable period of political bargaining. All the options for forming a new
government are beset by serious unresolved problems and, in the absence of a
new parliamentary majority, early elections could be called for next spring.
After weeks of mounting dissension between Mr Berlusconi and Mr Bossi, the
League leader announced his formal break with the government coalition on
Saturday. Mr Bossi said he was backing a no confidence motion to be proposed
jointly with Mr Rocco Buttiglione's Popular party (PPI), the heirs of the
Christian Democrats who dominated Italy's post-war politics until
discredited by the country's spate of corruption scandals.
Mr Bossi played down suggestions that his break with the government would
split the League and leave him as head of a small rump of the movement. In
recent days as many as 50 of the 163 League members in both houses have
talked of staying with Mr Berlusconi.
But Mr Bossi has proved an astute politician and it is significant that the
League has not directly associated itself with two other motions of no
confidence also being presented on Wednesday. One of these has been tabled
by the former communist Party of the Democratic Left (PDS), the main
opposition force, with which Mr Bossi has been in close contact.
An open alliance with the PDS is still rejected by many in the League
because of the former's communist past and its ambiguous relationship with
Reconstructed Communism, which represents the hardline core of the old
Italian Communist party (PCI).
Reconstructed Communism has tabled a third motion of no confidence. These
separate motions will have the benefit of allowing at least one trial run to
test the compactness of the League vote and the scale of opposition to Mr
Berlusconi. At the same time the three votes allow the League, as well as
the PPI, to signal their distance from the left.
Even if the League splits, it would be surprising if the anti-government
bloc failed to muster the 316 votes necessary to bring down Mr Berlusconi -
albeit by a slim margin.
The present coalition consists of Mr Berlusconi's Forza Italia movement, the
League, Mr Gianfranco Fini's neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance, and two
minor partners, the Christian Democratic Centre (CCD) and Radicals.
Altogether the coalition has 368 votes in the chamber of deputies, of which
the League accounts for 105.
The PDS-led Progressives have 167, while the PPI has 33. The 39 deputies of
Reconstructed Communism have said they will vote to bring down the
government.
The timing of Wednesday's no confidence votes still depends on completion of
the 1995 budget's progress through parliament. On Saturday night the Senate
gave its final stamp of approval.
Delaying tactics could be used on the final budget sessions this week in the
chamber of deputies by government supporters, thus postponing the confidence
debate.
</TEXT>
