<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 94 / Pressure for EU referendum set to grow: Move seen as way of
appeasing Eurosceptic MPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pressure on pro-European cabinet ministers to back a referendum on Britain's
future in Europe is set to intensify early next year amid signs that
rebellious Tory backbenchers will step up their feud with Mr John Major's
government.
As the cabinet prepares to work out its negotiating position for the next
stage of European Union integration, the government is being pressed to
promise a referendum on the issue in an effort to appease Tory Euro-rebels
in the Commons.
Mr Major and other ministers are expected to debate a referendum early in
the new year, when they discuss their negotiating position for the EU's
inter-governmental conference in 1996.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and
industry secretary, are among pro-European ministers who have already made
clear they are against consulting the British public over any deal signed at
the conference.
However, the pressure on both men to back a referendum looked set to grow
yesterday amid signs of a worsening feud between the government and the nine
Tory MPs who lost the party whip after voting against the European Finance
Bill this month.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, issued one of the sharpest attacks
yet on the group, arguing that their dissent threatened to consign the party
to the political wilderness.
'We have to remember that the Conservative party is not a debating society,
it is not indulging in internal discussion for some sort of literary
purpose,' he told BBC1's On the Record programme. 'Politics is about power.'
But one of the rebels, Mr Nicholas Budgen, MP for Wolverhampton South West,
demanded that the government rule out at once the possibility of joining a
single currency.
'The whip should be publicly offered back to us all at the same time,' he
wrote in the Mail on Sunday. 'This should be an occasion for generosity and
not for nitpicking and malice, comparing the character of the various
members of the group.'
At meetings of the cabinet's sub-committee on European questions next month,
ministers are expected to set out the broad direction they want the EU to
take into the next century.
In an effort to end deep divisions within the Conservative party over the
next stage of European integration, the cabinet may also agree the
conditions under which it would offer a referendum to the British people.
Friends of Mr Clarke said yesterday the chancellor might back a referendum
in the event that the IGC set Europe on a strongly pro-federalist path. 'I
think there will be a government announcement and one that will not leave
people isolated,' a close ally of the chancellor said. 'There has been a
move towards common ground in the cabinet in the last week or two. We can't
stick with the current uncertainty over a referendum because it's too
divisive.'
Blair warns against poll complacency, Page 6
Guide to 1996 inter-governmental conference, Page 11
</TEXT>
