<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Hedge funds settle claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Two US hedge funds agreed to pay Dollars 76m to settle charges that they
manipulated the US Treasury bond market in April 1991. Steinhardt Management
and Caxton had been accused by the Justice Department and the Securities and
Exchange Commission of a market 'squeeze', in which they conspired to corner
the market in two-year Treasury notes to drive up prices.
According to the authorities, they took positions worth Dollars 20bn in a
Dollars 12bn issue of notes, enabling them to make illegal profits of
Dollars 35m. The settlement, in which neither fund admitted or denied the
allegations, is unrelated to the bigger Treasury market 'squeeze' for which
Salomon Brothers admitted responsibility two years ago.
</TEXT>
