<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Mercosur customs union to begin on January 1
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OURO PRETO, BRAZIL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The four South American countries in the Mercosur trade group yesterday
settled all their differences and said they were ready for the trade area to
become a full customs union from January 1 as planned.
Foreign ministers from Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay reached
agreement on a number of outstanding problems after a hectic night of
negotiation.
The agreements will be included in the document, to be known as the protocol
of Ouro Preto, which is to be signed by the four presidents today and will
give Mercosur a similar legal status to the European Union.
Mr Celso Amorim, Brazil's foreign minister, said he was 'very proud' the
four countries had put in place the first customs union among developing
countries.
The protocol also sets out rules for the Mercosur institutions such as an
arbitration system for disputes and rules to promote competition and ease
customs procedures.
The four countries agreed the final lists of products, mainly those
considered unready to face full competition, which will be allowed to keep
domestic tariffs for four more years rather than cut tariffs to zero
immediately.
Brazil and Argentina, which together account for more than 95 per cent of
Mercosur's gross domestic product, also reached an accord on their
automotive industries. Because both countries consider this sector
strategic, it is given a special exemption from the free trade rules.
The protocol commits the four countries to review before 2001 when and
whether to go ahead toward a full common market, which implies the free
movement of goods and labour.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BRZ  Brazil, South America.
    ARZ  Argentina, South America.
    PYZ  Paraguay, South America.
    UYZ  Uruguay, South America.
</CN>
