<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / The monks' empty glass cabinet: The missing Codex Sinaiticus
sits in London. But should it be returned to its original home?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER ASPDEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This is a tale of two libraries. They are thousands of miles apart, but
united in their respect for scholarship and reverence for the written word.
They both, in their own way, contain awesome collections of manuscripts and
richly repay the effort of a visit. I have seen both in the past week and,
in the course of my travels, heard for the first time the sad story of the
Codex Sinaiticus.
The first visit was to the library of the Greek Orthodox monks of St
Catharine's monastery at the foot of Mount Sinai. The location is, as
promised in the ever-thickening piles of tourist brochures, spectacular, the
6th century church radiant with early Byzantine splendour.
The library, said our guide from the monastery, was laden with riches from
the early years of Christianity; but the jewel of their collection was
missing. He pointed to a glass case in the corner containing a few sheets of
parchment with Greek writing on them. A poorly-taken photograph was stuck on
the cabinet with Sellotape. It showed what should have been inside: the
Codex Sinaiticus, a 4th century bible regarded as one of the three most
important early versions of the holy book in existence.
Our guide, more in sorrow than in anger, told us the monks' side of the
story. The Codex was borrowed by a 19th century German scholar, Constantine
Tischendorf, who promised he would bring it back to its proper home. The
letter in which he made his pledge hangs on one of the church walls.
Instead, the Codex ended up in the hands of the Russian Tsar in St
Petersburg. There it remained until the Soviet government, which
unsurprisingly had little use for the tome, sold it to the British Museum in
1933, reputedly to help pay for the restoration of its embassy in London.
The monks' glass cabinet, in the meantime, has remained empty.
And so, a few days later, I visited my second library; not, strictly
speaking, a library at all, but room 30 of the British Museum in London,
which contains a staggeringly valuable collection of original documents and
volumes: Chaucer's Canterbury Tales, the Slavonic Gospels, Haydn's Drum-Roll
symphony; even a letter from John Lennon, bless him, to his old mucker
Stuart Sutcliffe.
And there, in an unobtrusive corner, the Codex Sinaiticus, next to the Codex
Alexandrinus, not too far from Nelson's Memorandum and a germ's leap away
from the culture plate on which Fleming discovered penicillin  - odd
bed-fellows to be sure, but part of the eclectic charm of the place, I
suppose.
I ranted to myself (and to a startled shop assistant) about the evils of
cultural imperialism and suddenly hated this cultured corner of Bloomsbury
which has caused so much distress round the world. But I instinctively felt
on dodgy ground. And so it proved.
The British Museum side of the story, as expressed in one of its books, soon
clears away the smokescreen of sentiment. Tischendorf, according to their
sources, actually rescued the pages of the Codex from being incinerated by
the monks for winter fuel. He then persuaded them to present the book to the
Tsar in appreciation of the protection of Holy Russia, in order to safeguard
it.
The guide in the monastery had heard the argument, and duly rubbished it
('How, then, did we manage to keep it in perfect condition for 15
centuries?'). But I spoke to a couple of authorities in the field who
confirmed my worst fears. The monks of St Catharine's at that time, it
seems, cared as much for their treasures as for a sack of coal. Their
attitude to antiquity, one of them told me, showed 'an irresponsibility that
beggars description'.
But that is not the end of the story; for today's monks are very aware
indeed of the value of their collection, and assure us that they know
exactly how to look after it. The rules of the game are different. Tourists
are beginning to flock to Sinai as they have traditionally flocked to
Bloomsbury, they listen to the monks' plight, they curse Europe's cynical
plunderers. The British Museum is finding it more and more difficult to play
the straight bat of rightful ownership; and rightly so. For possession is
only nine-tenths, after all, and when did the law ever capture hearts and
change minds anyway?
</TEXT>
<XX>
