<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Private View: Territorial champion - Christian Tyler meets
Jacques Blanc, the new president of the European Committee of the Regions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTIAN TYLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Give him an audience, and Jacques Blanc is airborne. Put him in front of a
home crowd, and he will stay aloft for an hour. I first witnessed the
aerodynamic talents of the mayor of La Canourge (pop. 2,000) at a
winegrowers' banquet in Narbonne in the French Midi.
Surfeited on oysters and bubbly, 500 guests had listened with indifference
to the exertions of a wine-glass percussionist. Politely they had applauded
the caped caballero who pranced among the tables on a white stallion. But
when Blanc took the stage to tell them what they wanted most to hear - that
they could once again become world-beating viticulturists - they responded
with intoxicated roars.
Wine is serious politics in the Languedoc-Roussillon region of which Blanc
is serving his second term as council president. And wine is the theme he
often uses to explain his new role as president of the European Committee of
the Regions, a Maastricht creation set up this year.
One of the pushiest politicians on the French right wing, the 55-year-old
Blanc brings the same aerated rhetoric to the committee's proceedings. Yet
even political adversaries concede that he is a smart operator. Never still,
rarely silent, he has ambition written all over him.
There were cries of 'Stitch-up]' when Blanc won the presidency of the
committee in March. The Socialists had two candidates, Pasqual Maragall of
Barcelona and Charles Gray of Strathclyde; they decided to run Maragall in
order not to split the Left vote.
According to Blanc, Maragall did a deal with the favourite, the Christian
Democrat prime minster of Flanders, Luc van den Brande. 'It was designed to
kill me,' he said. 'But I won.' Meanwhile, opponents claimed, Blanc had done
a deal with Maragall whereby if they led the ballot, they would swap the two
top jobs in 1996.
Over a stylish but workmanlike lunch with members of his entourage in
Brussels I asked Blanc why he had wanted the job so much.
'You underestimate the importance of the committee,' he replied. 'It is
always interesting for a politician to head a brand-new organisation.' The
committee of 189 elected politicians, ranging from regional barons to
municipal captains, is a diluted version of the body first envisaged. The
Germans once talked of it as a second chamber of the European parliament.
Blanc says its consultative function is still enough to give it great
influence over the life of Europe. 'To establish a new political reality in
Europe - there aren't many people who could do that. I consider that next to
the President of the Commission, of the Parliament and of the Council of
Ministers this is the most interesting job.'
But you are still mayor of La Canourge?
'I am the mayor, and I invite you to play golf,' he said with a flash of
teeth.
What do the villagers of La Canourge think you do in Brussels?
'First, they are quite proud. Second, my region and my town are among the
priority development zones and therefore they think Europe has brought them
money. Also that it helps them sell their agricultural products. They think
I am in Brussels too often. But they forgive me.' He leant back with a
satisfied laugh.
What do you do every week?
'I am saving Europe from despair.' He laughed again.
Jacques Blanc started life as a doctor, like his father, and worked as a
general practitioner in La Canourge. His curriculum vitae claims he was also
a neuropsychiatrist specialising in the treatment of handicapped children.
Why did you take up psychiatry?
Blanc gave his usual answer. 'Because it's always interesting to study the
reactions of men - and women.' Here he winked.
I recalled a fellow committee member saying that one thing Jacques Blanc
could not be accused of was paying too close attention to other people's
views. Now Blanc smiled and said: 'I think I was a very good generalist and
a very bad psychiatrist. I'm not mad enough to be a good psychiatrist.'
He went into politics because his Lozere region was turning into a desert.
Now it had registered the first population gain in 100 years. 'I am very
proud of that result, and Europe has contributed.'
From local councillor and mayor, Blanc ascended to the national parliament,
was secretary-general of Valery Giscard d'Estaing's Republican Party and
briefly Minister of Agriculture. When I asked him whether he thought of
himself as a still-rising star, or whether he had reached a plateau, he
said:
'I think a pleasant plateau. I'm not a candidate for the presidency of
France.'
Peaceful for the most part, Blanc's committee was torn apart last month when
it chose to give an opinion on reforming the wine market. Spanish and
Mediterranean members, who fortify their wine with concentrated grape
'must', almost came to blows with the Germans, who use sucrose.
Blanc may have thought he had disarmed north-south tension by announcing,
even before his election, that he would appoint Dietrich Pause, a
gentle-mannered German, as his chief official (the job the Germans wanted).
He would not admit to me that he had made a gaffe, but smoothly declared
that although the debate had been fierce there had been 'elements to satisfy
both sides'.
How can regions agree on anything, I asked, when they are in competition for
EU money?
'It's the essence of Europe to try to overcome what separates the different
entities and try to agree a common line,' Blanc replied. This had been
achieved on such important topics as regional aid (the cohesion fund) and
strengthening the devolution of power (subsidiarity).
The fact that you have large and small authorities on the committee must be
a problem.
'It could have been a blockage and I think most of my success is that I have
prevented it. And why? Because I am at the same time - forgive my lack of
modesty - a big one and a small one, president of a real region and mayor of
a small commune as legitimate as the mayor of Rome or Athens.
'For me there is no big, no small - only the elected representative,
anointed by the voters.'
The mandate of the committee will be renewed at next year's post-Maastricht
negotiation. Blanc hopes to achieve full autonomy from the economic and
social committee with which he has to share administration and paper clips.
He says he does not want control of EU funds.
Don't your electorates think you have money to give them?
'The distribution is conditioned by choices higher up. So if we influence
the big decisions, without ourselves opening the sluice we can have a say in
the water that flows. It is better to be at the source where the great flood
is than at the little pipi end of the tap.' He laughed.
Is there a danger the committee will encourage separatism? 'No.'
Why do people say they are afraid of it? 'Because they haven't understood
what regions are. I believe, on the contrary, that regionalism is the
antidote to separatism.
'I, who am from a centralised nation and defend the nation state, am not at
all bothered by being also spokesman of a region. I'll do it my way. I think
regionalism is the best answer to the complex problems we have in all our
countries, simultaneously reconciling respect for the state, the grand
European design, and the needs of identity.'
Nor, he said, did his committee present any kind of threat to the directly
elected Euro-MPs. 'That is not the way to look at it. It's a question of
complementarity. Euro-MPs have a European mandate. We are elected to exert
territorial influence on policy.'
But will regions one day, in the distant future, under a federal government,
be more important than nation states?
'No. I don't think so. Whether we like it or not, the way chosen is a Europe
of nation states, with, of course, all the different levels that constitute
them.'
Lunch was not over, and Blanc had about 20 minutes in which to catch a
flight to Paris. 'No,' he added, starting up from his chair and taking a
last slurp of coffee, 'the problem of our democracies is that the citizens
don't feel close to those who take the decisions. We have to rediscover that
proximity.'
An aide passed him his coat and briefcase. 'And when I see sometimes how
some of our friends (he seemed to be referring to the Germans) get stuck
over a comma, it shows they have misunderstood the role of the committee.
'When you are a legislator, a word is very important. But when you are being
consulted, it is not the word or the comma that matters, it is the spirit
which blows through it.'
With that, Jacques Blanc stretched out a hand and blew from the room.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9111 Executive Offices.
</IN>
<XX>
