<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Arts: Caribbean carnival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
At the Cochrane Theatre, the black Talawa company has found another offbeat
Christmas show to stage. This year it is Sylvia Wynter's Maskarade, with
music by Olive Lewin, which recreates a Jamaican street festival known as
'Jonkunnu'. (Nobody is quite sure why, but it may commemorate a man called
John Canoe.) For colour and verve, Yvonne Brewster's production scores high;
there is a certain intelligibility problem with the Jamaican dialect, but
that rather enhances the exotic charm of the piece.
The setting is Kingston in 1841, a year in which the Mayor rashly decided to
ban the Jonkunnu parade. The civil disorder that resulted barely crops up in
Maskarade, however, for it is not a political show. In the first act we
watch the local citizenry preparing for the carnival, planning their
costumes, jockeying for the best roles in the mummers' play; in the second,
we get the play itself, declaimed in quaint rhetoric amid a swirl of
fantastical costumes.
Those, like the stereotyped folk-characters who prance and revel in them,
carry half-remembered echoes from all over: Africa, courtly Europe, pure
local fantasy. The cast of ten - all-singing, all-dancing  - project
everything with terrific gusto, even when what they have to say is opaque to
non-Caribbean ears. (The Caribbean part of the audience relished many things
that passed the rest of us by.) This is a thoroughly professional cast, by
the way, not just talented amateurs, and any West Indian connections they
have probably go back a generation or two.
There are a lot of appealing songs, simple and mostly short, accompanied by
a trio sitting high on one side of Ellen Cairns' pretty set (an arrangement
of screens and straw carnival-figures). There are lively fusillades of
drumming. The whole show takes less than two hours, and ends with a touching
lament. Children might mind not being able to figure out just what, exactly,
is going on; but if they don't, they will probably enjoy everything else
about Maskarade.
</TEXT>
<XX>
