<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Arts: Surrealist show-cases - William Packer lifts the lid
on the latest exhibition at the Whitechapel gallery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM PACKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
We live out our lives with boxes from the cradle to the grave. By whatever
they hold, they describe and define what we are and would be, our fears and
hopes. We have only to lift the lid, open the box to discover who knows what
treasure, or secret, or horror. 'Open the box, OPEN THE BOX]' shrieks the
audience in gleeful anticipation.
Christmas boxes, chocolate boxes, match boxes, tool boxes, soap boxes, toy
boxes, dressing-up boxes, hat boxes, paint boxes, cigar boxes, knife boxes,
button boxes, shoe boxes, jewel boxes, pill boxes, make-up boxes, fuse boxes
 -we could go on with the list for ever.
For boxes mean lists too, and categories and collections - boxes full of sea
shells from those far-off beaches of childhood; cabinet drawers full of
birds' eggs plucked and blown so carefully in days before ornithological
correctness; match boxes full of beetles, spiders, moths and butterflies.
There is the remembered feel and rustle of tissue paper and cotton-wool, the
pulling open, the unwrapping, the oh so gentle picking up.
Boxes also mean the festivals, the games and discoveries of childhood, the
presents, the parties, the dressing up, the illicit searchings and
adventures through attics and cupboards, dressing-tables and
chests-of-drawers.
Small wonder then that artists should draw directly upon this common stock
of memory and experience. To surrealists in particular, including our
latter-day conceptualists, the box has been an obvious and constant theme.
There it is, to be taken as it is found, its contents ready-made. Or again
it is taken as it is but left unopened, declared by its label only in
imaginative possibility. Or yet again the label is the artist's own, and the
contents to be taken on trust. Or the contents, as the artist has supplied
them, are revealed or hinted at, the box itself become a stage or theatre in
miniature, quite literally a show-case.
The emphases and combinations are limitless in possibility, and any
exhibition of such work, whether brilliantly or indifferently chosen and
presented, can hardly fail to be fascinating. Indeed the material is so
dense that any particular disappointment may be immediately shrugged off for
the treat that follows. This show at Whitechapel, ending a national tour, is
true to that form and indeed holds many not just fascinating but beautiful
things.
Joseph Cornell, with his quietly theatrical and ambiguous narratives, sets
the pace, and from Schwitters' flattened cigarette carton, and such as Man
Ray, Eileen Agar, Arman, Meret Oppenheim, Louise Nevelson, Jiri Kolar and
Martial Raysse, to Earnshaw and Raynaud, surrealism supplies the substance
of the show. The upshot is that interest and surprise lie less in the nature
of the work than in its particular quality and in the artist who produced
it. I was especially intrigued by Avis Newman's little box of snails set in
waxed compartments, and delighted to see Fred Stiven's small and mysterious
boxed abstractions, self-effacing to a fault, given their proper prominence
at last.
But all that said, and the works of some of the artists - Cornell,
Schwitters, Stiven, Kolar and one or two others - excepted, one cannot but
come away feeling just a little let down. For so much of it seems amusing
enough, and clever, but also arch and self-conscious, easy and arbitrary, as
though anything else would have done just as well.
We are back to the tray of birds' eggs and the box of sea shells, and to the
drawers and cabinets full of nails and screws and clips and bolts in the
old-fashioned ironmonger's shop.
Worlds in a Box: Whitechapel Art Gallery, Whitechapel High Street E1, until
February 12; a National Touring Exhibition from the South Bank, sponsored by
British Telecom.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
