<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Outdoors: Fat skis send you flying - Arnie Wilson on how a
new type of ski allows almost anyone to go heli-skiing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARNIE WILSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Painting by numbers may not have produced many Rembrandts but it gives
pleasure to many would-be artists who might otherwise have difficulty
painting a shed.
And Bach might be turning in his grave at modern keyboards that play
themselves, but they bring the excitement of making music to uninitiated.
And now we have 'fat boys', which allow mediocre skiers to join the hitherto
elite and become heli-skiers - skiers who ride like Vietnam 'grunts' to
virgin snow in a clattering helicopter, there to ski in bottomless powder
where few have skied before.
So how, in the time it takes to don a powder suit in a telephone box, can
Average Skier become Super Skier?
Fat skis are the answer. They have sparked the off-piste revolution and this
winter, have taken a grip on heli-skiing.
The 'fat' ski was developed by ski manufacturer Atomic, based on a prototype
designed by a former Austrian train driver who had the idea of sawing a
snowboard in half. The original, the Atomic Powder Plus, was quickly
imitated by virtually all the main ski manufacturers.
The usual length is either 165cms or 185cms and because the ski is almost
twice as wide as a conventional ski it floats on the surface of powder
rather than burrowing deeply into it. They can bought or rented in most main
ski areas, but not in huge numbers as they are only really designed for
off-piste use.
So today, middle-aged intermediates who would have had a terrible struggle
to ski powder can now sign up for a week's helicopter skiing knowing that
the fat skis will be their passport to success. The only barrier to
heli-skiing now is cash, not skill.
But the question remains: is it right and proper that the rank and file
should be allowed to use this new equipment to penetrate the mystique of the
true artist or athlete?
Inevitably, those with a passion for the real thing might resent 'skills'
acquired so cheaply. Those skilful enough to heli-ski on ordinary skis tend
to resent the fact that their precious world - not to mention their sacred
powder - is being invaded by lesser beings.
Helicopter skiing is frowned upon in many parts of Europe, where
environmentalists have successfully managed to have it banned in most of
Austria and France. This leaves Switzerland as Europe's heli-skiing mecca,
with Italy another option.
The French get round the ban by transporting clients across the border into
Italy, where heli-skiing is permitted, and flying them to peaks from which
they can ski either in Italy or back into France. Helicopters are allowed to
collect skiers on French terrain at the end of the day from the bottom of
the mountain but not to take them to the top.
Grindelwald offers some of the best heli-skiing in the world, with huge
7,000ft vertical descents from such spots as Sustenalp and Rosenegg just
across the Eiger/Munch/Jungfrau massif.
There is good heli-skiing in New Zealand, the Himalayas and parts of what
was the Soviet Union, but North America - especially Canada - with its vast
wilderness areas, is where the sport of heli-skiing has become a
fully-fledged industry.
Resorts such as Sun Valley, Jackson Hole, Telluride, Whistler and Panorama
offer daily heli-ski outings, but if you want the 'total experience' you
should look at the option of spending a whole week in a heli-skiing lodge in
British Columbia where you live, breathe and dream helicopter skiing. It is
not cheap, but it is undoubtedly the best.
Canadian Mountain Holidays (CMH) runs lodges in nine areas, including the
celebrated Bugaboos, Cariboos, and Monashees.
If you are reluctant to be 'incarcerated' - however cosily and luxuriously -
in a wilderness lodge for a week, you have the option of basing yourself in
town: CMH offers excellent heli-skiing out of Revelstoke.
Its only serious rival is Mike Wiegele, whose operation is based in just one
location at Blue River but covers an enormous amount of terrain. While CMH
is the brand leader, both organisations are extremely professional and the
overall experience is similar. Fat skis now dominate Canadian heli-skiing.
Even most of the guides use them.
Skilled powder skiers determined not to pander to such toys can use
conventional skis, but the fat skis make it so much easier and less
energetic that they can find themselves being left behind by the fat
brigade.
CMH: Contact-Powder Skiing in North America, 61 Doneraile St, London SW6
6EW. Tel: 071-736 8191
Mike Wiegele Helicopter Skiing: Ski Scott Dunn, Fovant Mews, 12a Noyna Road,
London SW17 7PH. Tel: 081-767 0202; or Fresh Tracks, McMillan House, Cheam
Common Rd, Worcester Park, Surrey KT4. Tel: 081-875 9818
Heli-skiing in Grindelwald: Powder Byrne, 50 Lombard Street, London SW11
3SU. Tel: 071-223 0601
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3949 Sporting and Athletic Goods, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
