<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Take control of your
pension - Debbie Harrison examines a top-up plan that provides access to
low-cost equity funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Richard Gordon, a qualified accountant, asked Weekend Money to check the
availability of a special type of top-up plan for a company pension scheme.
'What I am looking for,' he explained, 'is a plan that provides 100 per cent
exposure to the UK equity market with a return that matches the FT-A
All-Share index. I'd like to combine this with minimum front-end costs and
annual management fees.'
One option worth considering is a little-known arrangement that allows
employees in occupational pension schemes to take control of their top-up
pension plans and gain access to low-cost, 100 per cent equity funds.
It appears that only one company - Personal Pensions Management (PPM) -
offers 'self-invested' free-standing additional voluntary contributions
(FSAVCs). Through the self-invested version, you can put money directly into
equities, authorised unit trusts (including index-tracking funds) and
investment trusts at more competitive rates than you get under standard life
office FSAVCs.
Self-invested FSAVCs are similar in many ways to self-invested personal
pensions (Sipps), which were introduced in the 1989 Budget to allow
knowledgeable investors either to run their own pension portfolio or appoint
a stockbroker to do it for them. The administration and legal documentation
is handled separately by a life office.
The beauty of this arrangement is that once you separate the two main
functions - investment and administration - you can, if you are dissatisfied
with the performance, change the stockbroker or investment manager without
having to change the provider.
Under a standard personal pension, where these two functions are combined,
you have to change the entire package and may lose out through
early-termination penalties.
Sipps can be used only by employees who are not in company pension schemes,
and the self-employed. Until recently, employees who wanted to top up their
company scheme benefits had to choose between their employer's in-house AVC
scheme, which often is invested conservatively, or take out an individual
FSAVC sold mainly by life offices.
Low-risk, in-house AVCs are ideal for employees close to retirement, but
younger pension scheme members are advised to go for funds with a high
equity content. FSAVCs offer a wide investment choice but can be expensive
to run.
In October 1992, the Inland Revenue confirmed that the self-invested option
applied also to FSAVCs. Initially, the charges on these plans were
considered to be high, but reductions have made them more competitive these
days.
PPM, part of the Swiss insurance giant Winterthur, is one of the leading
providers of Sipps and is thought to be the only company offering the
self-invested option for FSAVCs.
The annual charges on the self-invested FSAVC include a plan fee of Pounds
150 and an administration fee of 0.5 per cent, capped at Pounds 400 for
larger funds. On top of this, you would pay the stockbroker fees (where
applicable) and the charges on any unit or investment trusts.
The investment choice under a self-invested AVC includes UK and overseas
equities, unit trusts and investment trusts, insurance company managed funds
and unit-linked funds. Some unit-linked funds offer performance guarantees
backed by derivatives but these are expensive.
Gordon is keen to try a UK equity tracker fund which invests in a range of
companies on the FTA All-Share index. Trackers often are used by
institutional pension funds because they offer broad diversification and a
performance that should match closely the index that is followed.
Andrew Warwick-Thompson, head of partnership pensions at actuarial
consultant Bacon &amp; Woodrow, says: 'Normally, index trackers offer very low
charges compared with actively-managed funds, but these cost savings are not
usually passed on to the individual investor through authorised unit
trusts.'
Authorised unit trust index-tracker funds are offered by several
institutions including Gartmore, James Capel, Morgan Grenfell, Legal &amp;
General, Royal Life and Norwich Union. Of these, only Gartmore's UK Index
fund offers low-cost entry for smaller investments. Its minimum is Pounds
2,500 and there is no initial charge, while the annual management charge is
0.5 per cent. Other trackers typically impose a 5 per cent initial charge
and an annual charge of 0.75 per cent.
Gartmore's fund invests in 450 companies across all sectors, making it one
of the cheapest and best-diversified UK equity funds for individual
investors in pensions.
</TEXT>
