<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Wife is liable for IHT -
Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
My wife is a US citizen, aged 62. On January 1 this year, the Inland Revenue
recognised her as being domiciled in the US but resident in the UK, where we
have lived permanently since 1971. How does she stand over inheritance tax?
We suspect the Revenue's recognition of her US domicile is for general law
purposes, which would then apply to income tax and capital gains tax. But if
she has been resident in the UK for not less than 17 of the 20 years of
assessment, ending with the year of assessment in which the 'relevant time'
falls, then she will be deemed to be domiciled in the UK for IHT purposes.
Her world-wide assets would then be potentially liable to IHT on her death.
(Reply by Andrew White of Gordon Leighton &amp; Co.).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
