<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Companies): Directors' dealings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIVIEN MACDONALD, The Inside Track
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Traditionally Christmas is a period of good cheer in the City when the
market rallies, writes Vivien MacDonald of The Inside Track.
The absence of such a rally this year may make some people despondent, but
the number of directors beginning to buy shares again should offer a glimmer
of good spirits.
In the past, increasing numbers of directors buying has presaged a rise in
the market.
Better news is filtering in from the US where the bears are slightly in
retreat and the bulls are coming back. This would be genuinely good news for
the market though its impact may not come through till the new year.
Filofax, the company that supplies specialised stationery, has featured
several times in this column over the past year as directors have bought
large quantities of stock. The sale by Robert Collischon, the chairman, of
20,008 shares at 223p still leave him with over 1.76m shares.
The shares have performed well over the past year, recording an
out-performance of some 43 per cent relative to the market.
Williams Holdings is a group with diverse interests - ranging from homes and
garden through to specialist engineering. The shares have been performing
steadily. Earlier this year the company had a rights issue and the recent
sale made by AN Rudd was in order to fund the rights he took up at that
point.
