<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Weekend Money: Let's drink to '94, in castor oil - It was a
disappointing year overall, but at least it was healthy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It was a hell of a first half, but the rest of the year has left us
disappointed rather than devastated. Despite a couple of half-point rises in
short-term interest rates, the FT-SE 100 index stands slightly above its
end-June level of 2,919 and the long-dated gilt-edged yield has held at 8.6
per cent (although only after hitting an intermediate high point of 9 per
cent late in September).
Going back a year, however, the bull market enthusiasm was all-pervading.
The only way for the stock market was up, most analysts said. Some talked
about 4,000 on the Footsie, hardly any about 3,000.
My own opinion of the FT-SE 100 index at 3,400 was cynical. We were in the
late, panic-buying stage of the bull market, I said. Prices might
temporarily move higher, but equities were only for the brave and the
nimble. There was a chance that the dividend yield on the market as a whole
would be pushed down to 3 per cent - but, by then, all the warning lights
would be flashing red. In the event, it dipped no further than 3.2 per cent
at the market's peak on February 2.
Events unfolded a little more quickly than I had envisaged. January indeed
saw a dash from cash, as small investors piled into the two European
privatisation investment trusts which were launched opportunistically by
Mercury and Kleinwort Benson: they raised Pounds 1,075m between them, on
which original subscribers are showing an average loss of 17 1/2 per cent
now.
There was a smell of the notorious Royal Event: an over-hyped,
sucker-gathering, unit trust launch in September 1987. But it turned out to
be not quite so bad: instead of collapsing by 25 per cent in a few days, the
London stock market took nearly five months to fall by 18 per cent.
In fact, though, the equity shake-out was a bit of a sideshow. The real
story of 1994 has been one of a global bond market crash. Fixed-interest
securities finally shook off their boring image and staged a tumble as they
reversed the bull market of 1993 on a rather swifter timetable.
In 1993, long-dated gilt yields had fallen from 9 per cent late in January
to 6.5 per cent at the year-end, generating a total investment return for
1993 of 34 per cent - which was more than on equities. That movement had
been reversed entirely by September this year and, although there has been
some recovery since, the negative return on long gilts has been about 12 per
cent - a little worse than on equities. So much for the traditional idea
that bonds are less risky than shares.
The reason is partly that huge government deficits around the world have
collided with a vigorous economic recovery, pushing up bond yields. But the
scale of the boom and bust in global bonds has reflected the huge growth in
speculation by, among others, hedge funds and the so-called proprietary
trading teams of banks and securities houses.
Plenty about 1994 has been positive, however. Economic growth has soared
above expectations whereas inflation has under-shot. British companies as a
whole have become very prosperous, recording a record financial surplus in
the first half-year.
Yet, the stock market can seem perverse. Last year, I remarked that the
All-Share index had risen by 64 per cent in three years while dividends had
increased not at all. In 1994, dividends have bounded up by an unexpectedly
healthy 8 per cent but the All-Share has tumbled by 12 per cent.
Such share price behaviour might seem disappointing and puzzling to many
investors, but it is predictable. Remember that, in buoyant economic
conditions, it is not share prices that go up but expected rates of return.
Share prices fall so that equities can compete, in terms of future
potential, against price-insensitive competition - such as bonds issued by
free-spending governments. In a growing economy, capital is in greater
demand.
Fortunately, the British government - more nimbly than many others - is
reducing its borrowing requirement rapidly. But the influx of speculative
foreign money which flooded in during 1993 (when overseas buyers bought
Pounds 16.6bn of gilts) has halted, and been reversed slightly, in recent
months.
Essentially, the sharp rise in bond yields between February and June
reflected the necessary adjustment before domestic buyers would absorb all
that the Bank of England had to sell. Equities had to move roughly in line,
because a ratio between gilt-edged and equity yields of much more than 2 is
unsustainable. So, the yield on the All-Share has moved up to 4.1 per cent
now.
Not only securities have had a disappointing year in the UK. The feel-bad
factor has extended to housing, which has flattened out after a reasonably
promising spring-time rally. I was right to say in January that it was a
good moment to switch from the stock market into houses; but my forecast
late in 1993 that house prices would rise by up to 5 per cent over the next
year (which seemed cautious at the time) has been undermined by recent
setbacks. By November, house prices nationally were fractionally lower,
year-on-year.
Such house price weakness reflects the peculiar nature of the 1994 economic
recovery: a strong corporate sector has been driven by exports and healthy
flows through the capital markets, but consumers are restrained by job
insecurity, weak post-tax income growth, and a reluctance to increase their
debts.
Where, indeed, are the borrowers?
The banks and building societies have been confronted with major structural
challenges in 1994 - symptomised by the past year's mere 4 per cent growth
in broad money. This was the recovery that passed by the banks and house
prices, which depend traditionally for their strength upon voluminous
injections of mortgage finance, have languished.
This has been growth without a consumer spending spree and without a
borrowing binge. It is, of course, all thoroughly healthy. But so, they say,
is castor oil.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
    P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
