<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Markets Report: Sterling steady
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sterling was yesterday left unmoved by the ruling Conservative party's
massive defeat in the Dudley West by-election, writes Philip Gawith.
A poor showing by the government had been so widely discounted as to be of
negligible impact. The pound actually finished the day in London slightly
firmer, at DM2.4561 from DM2.4542, and at Dollars 1.563 from Dollars 1.5615.
For the most part, foreign exchanges were lost in a deep pre-Christmas
slumber. There was little currency movement of note, and volumes were in
some cases so low as to be derisory.
The Irish punt showed no reaction to the formation of a new government, and
in America the dollar was unresponsive to President Clinton's address in
which he promised Dollars 60bn in tax cuts over five years. It ended barely
changed at DM1.5714 and Y100.15. In New York the dollar finished at DM1.5727
and Y100.225.
In Europe, Mr Jacques Santer, incoming president of the European Commission,
said the Community would have failed if it had not achieved monetary union
by 1999. He said he hoped to achieve the third phase of monetary union by
1997.
The Irish punt showed almost no reaction to the formation of the new
government, resolving a month of political uncertainty. It finished at
IPounds 1.0164 against sterling, from IPounds 1.016.
Mr Jim Power, senior economist at the Bank of Ireland in Dublin, said:
'There is nothing in the programme of this government that could disturb
financial markets. The biggest threat on the interest rate front will be
when the UK next raises rates.'
The incoming government bolstered sentiment by pledging adherence to the
Maastricht convergence criteria.
Mr Power noted that the punt is not a heavily traded currency. 'Most of the
business is customer driven. Virtually no-one takes speculative positions in
the currency.'
The markets' apathetic response to the UK by-election result was explained
by Mr Nick Parsons, treasury economist at CIBC. 'To the extent that the
by-election defeat merely reflected expectations, it had no currency
impact.'
Some observers believe that President Clinton's tax plans could help the
dollar. They reason that the corollary of fiscal relaxation will be higher
interest rates in the current cycle, which should help the dollar.
In their fortnightly survey, the financial consultancy IDEA found that
respondents 'remained dollar bullish, but suggested on the whole that any
reasonable rally would wait until after the turn of the year'. On a
two-month outlook, respondents saw the dollar reaching DM1.59 and Y102.
Traders continue to watch the lira closely. Italian Prime Minister Silvio
Berlusconi has confirmed that there will be a vote of confidence next week,
which he could well lose.
Fanning the flames yesterday was Mr Umberto Bossi, head of the Northern
League, and member of the coalition government. He said he expected a change
of government in the new year.
The market remains confused about the implications. In the same IDEA survey,
the lira was a popular choice both as best and worst European currency in
1995. Respondents were more positive about sterling, with a net 20 per cent
looking for a bullish return.
The Bank of England cleared a Pounds 1.1bn money market shortage, at
established rates, in its daily operations.
</TEXT>
