<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / International Company News: GE plans share buy-back worth
Dollars 5bn over two years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
General Electric, the US conglomerate, is to buy back up to Dollars 5bn of
its shares over the next two years. This brings total buy-backs announced
this year by US corporations to a record Dollars 65bn, according to the Wall
Street firm Securities Data. The previous record was set in 1989 with
Dollars 62bn.
Mr Jack Welch, GE chairman, said 'we have concluded that GE stock today
represents the best investment we can make'.
The company has not bought in stock since 1992, having spent Dollars 5bn in
the period 1989-92. The programme originally announced in 1989 envisaged
purchases of up to Dollars 10bn.
Large buy-backs have accelerated in recent weeks, from companies such as
Merck, Chrysler and Walt Disney. However, the largest of the year was
Dollars 6bn from Philip Morris, the tobacco company, announced in August.
Mr Welch said the company's strong cash generation allowed it to continue
its capital investment programme, make complementary acquisitions and fund
share repurchases. Moody's, the debt rating agency, yesterday confirmed its
triple A rating on GE's debt. The company has gross borrowings of Dollars
5.9bn and cash of Dollars 3.7bn.
GE also said it would raise its quarterly dividend by 14 per cent to 41
cents a share. The company had lifted its dividend every year since 1975, it
said. The previous increase was 13 per cent last December.
This year, GE has suffered losses estimated at Dollars 1.5bn on Kidder
Peabody, its stockbroking subsidiary, which was hit by alleged fraud and is
now being sold off. However, its third-quarter profits were a record Dollars
1.37bn net, a rise of 13 per cent.
Mr Welch said he expected the buy-back programme to increase the rate of
growth in the company's earnings per share and its return on equity. GE
shares rose Dollars 1 1/4 to close at Dollars 50.
</TEXT>
