<PROFILE>_AN-ELSBYACKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941217
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / UK Company News: QMH details rescue package - Pounds 1.3bn
debt reconstruction could leave shareholders with 40%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Queens Moat Houses yesterday unveiled details of a Pounds 1.3bn rescue plan
almost two years after its shares were suspended, which could leave existing
investors with 40 per cent of the heavily indebted hotels group.
The stake is substantially higher than that won for shareholders recently in
other large debt reconstructions. At Heron, for example, shareholders have
been diluted down to 5 per cent.
The Queens Moat package includes a Pounds 200m debt for equity swap which
will allow existing shareholders to increase their stake. The swap is, in
effect, an equity issue underwritten by the company's banks which will be
priced at 8.6p. Few shareholders are expected to buy the shares at this
price.
The survival of Queens Moat is still in question, however, as one lender
continues to resist the package. It must be unanimously approved by the
company's 74 lenders before investors can vote on the proposals.
Queens Moat refused to comment on individual creditors, but it is believed
that the unhappy lender is California-based Trust Company of the West. TCW,
which bought the debt in the secondary market, is thought to disagree with
its ranking relative to other creditors.
Mr Andrew Coppel, the chief executive brought in by the banks to replace the
company's founder Mr John Bairstow last year, said he was confident the
proposals represented a good deal for creditors and shareholders. 'The
alternative is stark,' he said. 'The group would have to cease to trade.'
Under these proposals, Mr Coppel said, Queens Moat would not have to return
to shareholders for further finanical support. However, investors would be
unlikely to receive a dividend in the foreseeable future.
In addition to the debt swap, which will give ordinary shareholders 24 per
cent of the company and preference holders 16.2 per cent, Pounds 630m of the
Pounds 1.3bn debt will be restructured into longer-term and convertible
borrowing. This will be payable between 2000 and 2008.
The convertible instruments allow for a second debt for equity swap, at the
board's discretion, which could leave lenders with 75 per cent control. Mr
Coppel did not expect the second swap would be necessary; it was there as
protection in the event of unforeseen difficulties.
Other elements include the conversion of preference shares into ordinary
equity on substantially enhanced terms and amendments to debenture stock
terms.
Finally, banks have agreed to waive Pounds 43m in interest accrued since the
beginning of the year. This is roughly equal to the fees which Queens Moat
has incurred in the negotiations.
After the restructuring, Queens Moat's net liabilities would be Pounds 184m.
A circular detailing the proposals will be sent to shareholders in the new
year if the final lender agrees to the terms. This would open the way for
the shares to resume trading in the spring.
One substantial institutional shareholder said he was likely to back the
proposals. 'The banks could have left equity holders with nothing,' he said.
Now that the restructuring is largely out of the way, however, shareholders
will begin tackling operational issues, such as management, he added. 'It is
not necessarily the case that the people with the qualifications to get the
finanical restructuring out of the way are the right people to  .. run a
hotel company.'
Queens Moat has been in negotiations with bankers since April 1993, when it
became apparent it would breach certain loan covenants. Subsequent
valuations wiped Pounds 1bn off its property portfolio and last year the
group reported the second biggest loss in UK corporate history.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Queens Moat Houses.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7011 Hotels and Motels.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>FIN  Share issues.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
