<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 94 / Letters to the Editor: Bizarre airport charge formula
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr DERMOT COX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Des Wilson is right (Letters, December 14) that BAA's landing charges
are low compared with those at airports in other countries. This is the
result of a bizarre policy by BAA's regulator, the Civil Aviation Authority,
whose response to BAA's monopoly has been to force it to cut its charges
over the past two years (the retail price index minus 8 formula).
We have a situation at Heathrow where the demand for slots far exceeds
supply and where the airport is the largest single source of noise and air
pollution in London - yet charges are going down] The correct regulatory
solution is to allow market clearing prices and tax BAA's excess profits.
This special treatment of the air transport industry is also seen in the
exemption of airlines from paying any duty or tax on the fuel they use -
contrast the government's determination to put VAT on domestic power and the
massive levy on petrol and diesel.
Dermot Cox,
Heathrow Association for the Control of Aircraft Noise,
c/o 22 Ruskin Avenue,
Kew, Richmond TW9 4DJ
</TEXT>
